"Uggetti E., Ferrer I., Molist J., García J.","Technical, economic and environmental assessment of sludge treatment wetlands",2011,"Water Research","45","2",,"573","582",,,10.1016/j.watres.2010.09.019,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650418891&partnerID=40&md5=6a33e58961356ae8545b35bf73d3b430","Environmental Engineering Division, Department of Hydraulic, Maritime and Environmental Engineering, Technical University of Catalonia, C/Jordi Girona 1-3, Building D1, E-08034 Barcelona, Spain; Agència Catalana de l'Aigua, c/Provença 204-208, E-08036 Barcelona, Spain","Uggetti, E., Environmental Engineering Division, Department of Hydraulic, Maritime and Environmental Engineering, Technical University of Catalonia, C/Jordi Girona 1-3, Building D1, E-08034 Barcelona, Spain; Ferrer, I., Environmental Engineering Division, Department of Hydraulic, Maritime and Environmental Engineering, Technical University of Catalonia, C/Jordi Girona 1-3, Building D1, E-08034 Barcelona, Spain; Molist, J., Agència Catalana de l'Aigua, c/Provença 204-208, E-08036 Barcelona, Spain; García, J., Environmental Engineering Division, Department of Hydraulic, Maritime and Environmental Engineering, Technical University of Catalonia, C/Jordi Girona 1-3, Building D1, E-08034 Barcelona, Spain","Sludge treatment wetlands (STW) emerge as a promising sustainable technology with low energy requirements and operational costs. In this study, technical, economic and environmental aspects of STW are investigated and compared with other alternatives for sludge management in small communities (&lt;2000 population equivalent). The performance of full-scale STW was characterised during 2 years. Sludge dewatering increased total solids (TS) concentration by 25%, while sludge biodegradation lead to volatile solids around 45% TS and DRI24h between 1.1 and 1.4 gO2/kgTS h, suggesting a partial stabilisation of biosolids. In the economic and environmental assessment, four scenarios were considered for comparison: 1) STW with direct land application of biosolids, 2) STW with compost post-treatment, 3) centrifuge with compost post-treatment and 4) sludge transport to an intensive wastewater treatment plant. According to the results, STW with direct land application is the most cost-effective scenario, which is also characterised by the lowest environmental impact. The life cycle assessment highlights that global warming is a significant impact category in all scenarios, which is attributed to fossil fuel and electricity consumption; while greenhouse gas emissions from STW are insignificant. As a conclusion, STW are the most appropriate alternative for decentralised sludge management in small communities. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Biosolids; Composting; Constructed wetlands; Drying reed beds; Sanitation, wastewater","Constructed wetlands; Decentralised; Electricity-consumption; Environmental aspects; Environmental assessment; Land applications; Life-cycle assessments; Low energies; Operational costs; Post treatment; Significant impacts; Sludge dewatering; Sludge management; Sludge treatment; Small community; Stabilisation; Sustainable technology; Total solids concentrations; Volatile solid; Wastewater treatment plants; Biodegradation; Biological materials; Biological water treatment; Biosolids; Centrifugation; Composting; Fossil fuels; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Life cycle; Rating; Wastewater; Wastewater treatment; Water treatment plants; Wetlands; Environmental impact; fossil fuel; biodegradation; biosolid; composting; constructed wetland; economic analysis; environmental impact; environmental technology; fossil fuel; life cycle analysis; performance assessment; sanitation; sludge; waste treatment; wastewater; acidification; article; biodegradation; biosolid; carbon footprint; centrifuge; compost; composting; constructed wetland; cost effectiveness analysis; economic evaluation; energy consumption; environmental economics; environmental impact; 